Long_Description:
Willingdon Heights takes its name from Willingdon Avenue, the North Burnaby arterial named for Lord Willingdon, Canada's Governor General from 1926 to 1931 — and the neighbourhood itself dates largely from the decades that followed. Walk its streets between Boundary Road and Willingdon Avenue and you can read the timeline: wartime and postwar bungalows, the boxy Vancouver Specials that filled in mid-century lots, and now a fast-growing layer of duplexes and multiplexes as Burnaby's densification pushes north from the Brentwood Town Centre high-rise district next door.

That property mix is exactly why local knowledge matters for {SERVICE}. A 1950s bungalow off Madison or Carleton Avenue presents very different challenges than a two-year-old infill duplex — older materials, decades of settling, and systems that have been renovated in stages. {COMPANY_NAME} sees both every week, and our {BUSINESS_TYPE} approach adapts to each: {SERVICE_DESCRIPTION}

Geography plays its part too. Willingdon Heights sits on the gentle slope that runs down toward Burrard Inlet, just below the Hastings Street shops it shares with Burnaby Heights, one kilometre north. Metro Vancouver's oceanic climate delivers most of its rain between November and March, and on these older blocks that sustained wet season shows up as moisture, drainage, and moss and algae pressure on exteriors — conditions any {SERVICE_CATEGORY} provider working here has to plan around, not react to.

The neighbourhood's position also makes it a natural base for coverage. Boundary Road is the Vancouver–Burnaby line, so Renfrew Heights sits only three kilometres west; central Burnaby is four kilometres away, and Government Road about five. When a Willingdon Heights homeowner calls {PHONE}, they're reaching a team already working this corridor daily — which is how we keep our {RESPONSE_TIME} response commitment realistic rather than aspirational.

Economically, this pocket reflects Metro Vancouver's broader story: a region powered by the Port of Vancouver, film production, tech, and construction, where housing near rapid-transit-served hubs like Brentwood carries premium value. Protecting that investment is the point. Whether you own a character-era bungalow, a Vancouver Special, or a new multiplex unit, {COMPANY_NAME} delivers {SERVICE} built for how Willingdon Heights actually lives — starting with a straightforward {ESTIMATE_TYPE}. {UNIQUE_VALUE_PROP}
